7. See Richard Rorty, Philosophy and the Mirror of Nature (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1979); and Contingency, Irony, and Solidarity (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1989).

8. One of the best arguments for how these two notions of ‘modern’ relate is Marshall Berman, All That is Solid Melts into Air: The Experience of Modernity (New York: Penguin, 1988).

9. Steven Best and Douglas Kellner, The Postmodern Turn (New York: Guilford, 1997), especially pp. 24-5, and Steven Best and Douglas Kellner, Postmodern Theory: Critical Interrogations (New York: Guilford, 1991), pp. 29-32.

