72. For example, David Held, Democracy and the Global Order: From the Modern State to Cosmopolitan Governance (Stanford: Stanford University Press, 1995); and Jürgen Habermas, ‘Crossing Globalization’s Valley of Tears’，New Perspective Quarterly 17(4) (Fall 2000), pp. 51-57. For a rather different analysis of culture and globalization that also accepts the demise of the nation-state and hopes that it can result in diasporic public spheres of a more progressive postnational politics, see Arjun Appadurai, Modernity at Large: Cultural Dimensions of Globalization (Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Press, 1996).

